E. 127 How great the wis-dom, power, and grace, Which in re-demp-tion shine ! 3 The heavenly host with joy con - fess The work is all di vine. 160 'Let all the angels of God worship him." 533 Praying for a holy heart. HOW great the wisdom, power, and grace, Which in redemption shine 0 FOR a heart to praise my God, A heart from sin set free ! The heavenly host with joy confess A heart that always feels thy blood The work is all divine. So freely spilt for me!- 2 Before his feet they cast their crowns,- 2 A heart resign'd, submissive, meek, Those crowns which Jesus gave,- My great Redeemer's throne,- And, with ten thousand thousand tongues, Where only Christ is heard to speak, Proclaim his power to save. Where Jesus reigns alone. 3 They tell the triumphs of his cross, 3 O for a lowly, contrite heart, The suff'rings which he bore,- Believing, true, and clean ! How low he stoop'd, how high he rose, Which neither life nor death can part And rose to stoop no more. From him that dwells within: 4 O let them still their voices raise, 4 A heart in every thought renew'd, And still their songs renew; And full of love divine; Salvation well deserves the praise Perfect, and right, and pure, and good,- Of men and angels too ! A copy, Lord, of thine. 528 591 The act of consecration. Opening worship. LE Him to whom we now belong ONCE more we come before our God; His sovereign right assert! Once more his blessings ask: And take up every thankful song, O may not duty seem a load, And every loving heart. Nor worship prove a task ! 2 He justly claims us for his own, 2 Father, thy quick' ning Spirit send Who bought us with a price: From heaven, in. Jesus' name, The Christian lives to Christ alone, To make our waiting minds attend, To Christ alone he dies. And put our souls in frame. 3 Jesus, thine own at last receive, 3 May we receive the word we hear, Fulfil our hearts' desire; Each in an honest heart; And let us to thy glory live, And keep the precious treasure there, And in thy cause expire ! And never with it part. 4 Our souls and bodies we resign; 4 To seek thee all our hearts dispose, With joy we render thee To each thy blessings suit, Our all, no longer ours, but thine And let the seed thy servant SOWS, To all eternity. Produce abundant fruit.
